<h3 id="Constants">Constants<a class="anchor-link" href="#Constants">¶</a></h3><p>You can also change the values of constants used in the fft computatiion. When you load the data from dat files with <code>load_all</code> the function looks for the values of these constants in the dat file headers and saves them in the attributes of the returned dataset. It uses these values when computing the fft.</p>
<p><code>addProfileToDs</code> also uses these constants for the fft computation (in fact <code>load_all</code> calls <code>addProfileToDs</code> to compute the profiles).</p>
<p>To change the value of these setting used in the fft you can pass a dictionary including the new constants as follows:</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=36560a49">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In [37]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
<div class="cm-editor cm-s-jupyter">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">constants</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'c'</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="mf">1e8</span><span class="p">}</span>
<span class="n">differentConstants</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">out_from_gen_xarray</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">chirp</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">computeProfile</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">constants</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">constants</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">max_range</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1500</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">differentConstants</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dB</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=50728235">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">

</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Computing-displacements">Computing displacements<a class="anchor-link" href="#Computing-displacements">¶</a></h2><p>You can use functions built in to XApRES tom compute phase differences between profiles and convert them to displacements, along with the associated uncertainties.</p>
<h3 id="...from-two-profiles">...from two profiles<a class="anchor-link" href="#...from-two-profiles">¶</a></h3><p>For example, let's load two bursts separated by 1 month. THis time we will use a dataset from Thwaites Glacier, West Antarctica</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs" id="cell-id=938f0adb">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In [ ]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
<div class="cm-editor cm-s-jupyter">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">from_zarr</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">xa</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">load</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">load_zarr</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'gs://ldeo-glaciology/apres/thwaites/continuous/ApRES_LTG/zarr/full.zarr'</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1">#</span>

<span class="n">p1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">from_zarr</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">time</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'2023-07-17'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">isel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">time</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">profile_stacked</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">load</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">p2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">from_zarr</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">time</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'2023-07-19'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">isel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">time</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">profile_stacked</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">load</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=87e5a868">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>Note that in the first line above <code>from_zarr.sel(time='2022-07-17')</code> selects al the data from the 17th of JUly 2022, then <code>.isel(time=0)</code> selects the first burst from that day. In the second line above the asame thing is done for the 19th. We then also select just the stacked profile (with <code>.profile_stacked</code>) and then load the dta into memory with <code>.load()</code>; it is lazily loaded by default.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=8e42cd14">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>To compute the displacement between the two profiles we use the function <code>xapres.utils.compute_displacement</code>  as follows. This produces a  new xarray DataSet containing the original profiles and the following quantities computed in vertical bins</p>
<ul>
<li>the coherence between the profiles,</li>
<li>the phase difference,</li>
<li>the displacement</li>
<li>and the uncertainty in the displacement and phase difference.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=8d813239">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In [ ]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
<div class="cm-editor cm-s-jupyter">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">profiles</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">xa</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">utils</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">compute_displacement</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p2</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">profiles</span> 
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell-outputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-OutputCollapser jp-Cell-outputCollapser">
</div>

<h3 id="...from-multiple-profiles">...from multiple profiles<a class="anchor-link" href="#...from-multiple-profiles">¶</a></h3><p>You can also feed in multiple profiles to <code>compute_displacement</code> and it will compute the displacement between each profile and the neighbouring one:</p>

<span class="n">t2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">from_zarr</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">profile_stacked</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">isel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">time</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="nb">slice</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">))</span>

<h2 id="Sonfiying-the-ApRES-data">Sonfiying the ApRES data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Sonfiying-the-ApRES-data">¶</a></h2><p>As described <a href="https://ldeo-glaciology.github.io/glaciology-intro-book/sections/radar/apres/theory_1.html#compute-the-frequency-difference">here</a>, the chirps have frequencies in the kHz range are are therefore auduble to humans and can be straightforwardly 'sonified', i.e. turned in to sound.</p>
<p>The method <code>.sonify()</code> is added to xarrays produced by XApRES. It plays the chirp through your computer's speakers and, optionally, saved the sound in a common sound format (.wav).</p>
<p>It requires two additional packages that can be installed with</p>
</div>

</pre></div>

<p>The following code calls the sonify method. Note that in this case you first need to load the data to disk with <code>.load()</code> because the data is only alzily loaded in from_zarr by default. The methods we applied to lazily loaded data above (e.g., <code>.mean()</code> and <code>.plot()</code>) are designed to deal with lazily loaded data, but the functions used within <code>.sonify()</code> are not, hence why you need to fully load the chirp to disk before applying <code>.sonify()</code>:</p>
